ns.
 The 4-momentum of a particle is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P^{\mu}=(E,\overrightarrow{p})\label{4-momentum}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where E is the particle's energy and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overrightarrow{p}$
\end_inset

 is its spacial momentum.
 The invariant mass of the particle, which is the same in all frames of
 reference can also be defined
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{0}^{2}=E^{2}-\left\Vert \overrightarrow{p}\right\Vert ^{2}\label{Invarient Mass}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the rest mass of the particle, the invariant mass.
 Using the invariant mass through this equality is a strong tool when addressing
 decays, as demonstrated below.
 In conjunction with the invariant  mass, another fundamental conservation
 is that of the 4-momentum in a certain frame of reference, which along
 with the invariant  mass can yield info about the particle (e.g its mass
 and energy).
 Suppose a particle decays into two particles whose momenta and masses are
 known 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1},\overrightarrow{p}_{1},m_{2},\overrightarrow{p}_{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1},\overrightarrow{p}_{1}$
\end_inset

 are the corresponding mass and momentum of the first particle and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2},\overrightarrow{p}_{2}$
\end_inset

are the corresponding mass and momentum of the second particle.
 Using the conservation of 4-momentum before and after the decay and the
 invariant  mass in 
