\begin_layout Subsection

\size normal
Charged Particle in a Magnetic Field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
As explained in the following section, the particles will go through a spectrome
ter whose purpose is to measure the momentum of the particle.
 This is done by inducing a uniform magnetic field in a direction perpendicular
 to the direction of the particle's propagation for a known length, thus
 applying Lorentz force on the particle given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F=qv_{\perp}B\label{Lorentz force}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the particle's charge and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{\perp}$
\end_inset

is the velocity in the direction perpendicular to the magnetic field.
 As a result of the force, the particle will deviate from its original track
 until it reaches the end of the spectrometer.
 The curvature of its trajectory can then be measured, (supposing it has
 an electric charge, otherwise this method will prove ineffective) and by
 using Newton's second law and the circular motion of the charged particle
 inside the spectrometer, the particle's momentum can be extracted using
 the equation
